=========================================================
Q: What is a Component in React?
=========================================================
--> A component in React is a reusable, independent piece of UI.

--> It represents a part of the user interface and controls how that part looks and behaves.

üëâ In simple words:
       Components are the building blocks of a React application or function that returns jsx.
       --> component must be named in PascalCase(capital letter at start).

Q: Advantages or Why Components Are Important?
________________________________________
From an interview point of view, emphasize these 5 key benefits (easy to remember üòÑ):

1. Reusability ‚Äì Write once, use multiple times
------------
2. Separation of concerns ‚Äì Each component handles its own logic and UI
---------------------
3. Maintainability ‚Äì Easy to debug and update
-----------------
4. Readability ‚Äì Code becomes cleaner and structured
---------------
5. Testability ‚Äì Components can be tested independently
---------------

Types of Components in React
___________________________________

1. Functional Components (Most Common Today)
-------------------------------------------------
--> Written as JavaScript functions
--> Use Hooks for state and lifecycle
--> Preferred in modern React

function Welcome(props) {
  return <h1>Hello, {props.name}</h1>;
}

Q: How to create Functional Components ?
=============================================

1Ô∏è‚É£ Create a Component (Function Component) :
-----------------------------------------------
function Card() {
  return <h1>Hello from Card Component</h1>;
}
export default Card;

2Ô∏è‚É£ Use the Component : should use or call or render the component like this <Card/>
--------------------------------
import Card from "./Card";

function App() {
  return <Card />;
}
export default App;

Example : 

import { createRoot } from "react-dom/client";
import reactLogo from "./assets/react.svg";
import "./index.css";

function CardComponent(){
  return (    
    <div className="card">
    <h1 className="heding">
      <img className="logo" src={reactLogo} alt="images not found" />
      What is JSX ?
    </h1>
    <ul className="listitems">
      <li>Write HTML inside JavaScript.</li>
    </ul>
    <h1 className="heding">
      <img className="logo" src={reactLogo} alt="React Logo" />
      Rules of JSX
    </h1>

    <ul className="listitems">
      <li>Must enclose JSX in a root element</li>
      <li>Close all tags properly</li>
      <li>Use className instead of class</li>
      <li>Use camelCase for attributes</li>
      <li>Use curly braces for JavaScript</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
    )  
}
createRoot(document.getElementById("root")).render(<CardComponent/>);

‚≠ê Key Interview Point :
   --> A React component is a reusable JavaScript function that returns JSX.
   --> Simple and lightweight
   --> Use useState, useEffect, etc.
   --> Faster and easier to read


2. Class Components (Older Approach , Depricated)
---------------------------------
--> Written using ES6 classes
--> Use this.state and lifecycle methods

class Welcome extends React.Component {
  render() {
    return <h1>Hello, {this.props.name}</h1>;
  }
}

Key points:
-----------------
--> Uses lifecycle methods like componentDidMount
--> Less preferred now, but still important to understand


Props and State (Very Important Question!)
----------------------------------------------
1. Props
---------
--> Short for properties
--> Used to pass data from parent to child

Read-only
---------
<Welcome name="React" />

2. State
---------
--> Manages dynamic data inside a component
--> Can change over time 
--> E.g: const [count, setCount] = useState(0);


Component Lifecycle (Mention Briefly)
__________________________________________
1. For functional components: useEffect() handles lifecycle behavior
--------------------------
2. For class components:  a. componentDidMount    b. componentDidUpdate     c. componentWillUnmount
--------------------------

Example: Real-World Analogy (Interview Friendly)
----------------------------------------------
Think of a website like a car üöó:
Header ‚Üí Component
Footer ‚Üí Component
Button ‚Üí Component
Form ‚Üí Component

Each part works independently but together forms the complete app.

üîπ What are Props in React?
==================================
--> Props are immutable data passed from parent to child components to control their behavior and appearance.

üîπ Why Props Are Needed : 

Without props:
--> Components would be static
--> Code duplication increases
--> Reusability is lost

With props:
--> Same component can display different data
--> Logic and UI become modular
--> Follows component-based architecture

Example:
1. <ProfileCard name="Ajay" role="React Developer" />
2. <ProfileCard name="Rahul" role="Java Developer" />

üîπ How Props Work (Data Flow)
--> React follows one-way data binding:

|--------------------|
|Parent Component    |
|      ‚Üì (props)     |
|Child Component     |
|--------------------|

Step1: Parent sends data

Step2: Child receives data
--> Child cannot modify props

Note: 
This ensures:
--> Predictable behavior
--> Easy debugging
--> Better performance

üîπ Basic Example (Interview Friendly)
----------------------------------------
1. Parent Component
------------------
<ProfileCard myName="Ajay" role="React Developer" />

2. Child Component
------------------
function ProfileCard(props) {
  return (
    <h1>{props.myName} - {props.role}</h1>
  );
}

üîπ Props Are Immutable (VERY IMPORTANT)
-------------------------------------------
‚ùå This is NOT allowed:

props.myName = "Rahul"; // ‚ùå


‚úÖ Correct way:
--> Props should only be read
--> If data must change ‚Üí use state

Interview line: Props are immutable; state is mutable.


üîπ Props Destructuring (Best Practice)
----------------------------------------
Instead of: props.myName

Use:
function ProfileCard({ myName, role }) {
  return <h1>{myName} - {role}</h1>;
}
‚úî Cleaner code
‚úî Easier readability
‚úî Preferred in professional projects

üîπ Passing Different Types of Props
-------------------------------------
1. String
<Comp title="Hello" />

2. Number
<Comp age={25} />

3. Boolean
<Comp isActive={true} />

4. Array
<Comp skills={["React", "JS", "CSS"]} />

5. Object
<Comp user={{ name: "Ajay", role: "Developer" }} />

6. Function (Callback)
<Comp onClick={handleClick} />

Note: Passing functions enables child-to-parent communication.

üîπ Default Props (Fallback Values)
--------------------------------------
--> Used when parent does not send a value.

function ProfileCard({ role = "Frontend Developer" }) {
  return <h3>{role}</h3>;
}

‚úî Prevents undefined errors
‚úî Improves robustness

üîπ Props vs State (Common Interview Question)
-------------------------------------------------

| Props                  | State                        |
| ---------------------- | ---------------------------- |
| Read-only              | Mutable                      |
| Passed from parent     | Managed within component     |
| Used for configuration | Used for dynamic behavior    |
| Cannot be modified     | Can be updated with setState |

üîπ Props vs Context API (Advanced)
------------------------------------------

| Props                   | Context              |
| ----------------------- | -------------------- |
| Passed manually         | Globally accessible  |
| Can cause prop drilling | Solves prop drilling |
| Simple & explicit       | Good for large apps  |

Note: Use props for local data, context for global data.

üîπ Props and Reusability (Key Interview Point)
--------------------------------------------------
Props allow:
--> Same component ‚Üí multiple uses
--> UI separation from data
--> Scalable architecture
   E.g; <ProfileCard {...user} />


